<div id="review_3082979915" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3082979915" />
    <a title="Amy Imogene Reads" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/84702001-amy-imogene-reads"><img alt="Amy Imogene Reads" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548082309p2/84702001.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3082979915?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amy Imogene Reads" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amy Imogene Reads" href="/user/show/84702001-amy-imogene-reads">Amy Imogene Reads</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/84702001-amy-imogene-reads?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/84702001-amy-imogene-reads?shelf=read-in-2020">read-in-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/84702001-amy-imogene-reads?shelf=mystery-thriller">mystery-thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3082979915" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4532199217543023210">5 stars<br/><br/>While all the books in this series are great, this one was a real standout. Gamache&apos;s adventures in this one broke my heart and healed it all at once. <br/><br/><i>How the Light Gets In</i> is the 9th book in the Inspector Gamache series. Please check out Still Life to hear my thoughts on the first book in the series, if you are interested in reading these (which you should be, they&apos;re amazing). <br/><br/>Armand Gamache has had better days. After the wrenching conclusions of The Beautiful Mystery, Gamache finds him</span>
  <span id="freeText4532199217543023210" style="display:none">5 stars<br /><br />While all the books in this series are great, this one was a real standout. Gamache's adventures in this one broke my heart and healed it all at once. <br /><br /><i>How the Light Gets In</i> is the 9th book in the Inspector Gamache series. Please check out Still Life to hear my thoughts on the first book in the series, if you are interested in reading these (which you should be, they're amazing). <br /><br />Armand Gamache has had better days. After the wrenching conclusions of The Beautiful Mystery, Gamache finds himself alone in the days leading up to Christmas. His wife, Reine-Marie, is expecting him to join their son in Paris for the holiday, but Gamache has a few things to wrap up first. <br /><br />Myrna Landers, the used bookstore owner in Three Pines calls and asks for Gamache's help. Myrna has never asked for help before, and Gamache knows this time is different. He quickly makes the trek to Three Pines. <br /><br />Myrna's old friend is missing. Gamache is on the case. <br /><br />While Gamache is solving this case of a missing octogenarian, there is another plot line coming to a conclusion. Gamache's boss, Sylvain Francoeur, has had it in for Gamache for several years since Gamache landed his old friend in jail. Gamache's previous work in culling the rot from the corrupt police force didn't finish the job—and now the remaining rot has grown into something bigger, and considerably more deadly. <br /><br />It's really hard to talk about this one without spoiling anything, but I think this is in the top 5 of the series. The plot, the character development, and the sense of pacing were flawless. I couldn't stop reading, and when I got to the end it was an adrenaline-soaked thrill ride of brilliantly executed reveals, action, and conclusion.<br /><br /><a href="https://www.amyimogenereads.com/" rel="nofollow noopener">Blog</a> | <a href="https://www.instagram.com/amyimogenereads/" rel="nofollow noopener">Instagram</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="4532199217543023210" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


